508. ut sis sciens, for ut setas. Cf. 775. This is an early instance of the tendency of Latin, as of other languageS, to become ‘analyti03’ i. e. to express changes of case, tense, mood, voice, etc. by the addition of separate words, e. g. ‘prepositions, auxiliary verbs, etc., instead of by ease-endings or verbal terminations, etc. This latter method is called ‘synthetic.’ Greek is a good example of a ‘synthetic ' language, English of an ‘ analytie ' language. Instances of this ‘analytic' tendency are found in Euripides, and frequently in Hellenistic Greek.
